🔴 Kubernetes Architecture -----------------
  Control Plane (Master Node) – manages the cluster
  Worker Nodes – run the applications (containers)

  1️⃣ Control Plane (Cluster Brain)
    Definition:
    The Control Plane manages the entire Kubernetes cluster and makes decisions like scheduling pods, scaling, and maintaining the desired state.

    🚩Core Components
      1. kube-apiserver
        Entry point of the Kubernetes cluster
        All kubectl commands, API calls, and UI requests go through it
        Validates and processes REST requests
  
        Interview Insight
        No component talks directly with others; everything communicates via API Server.

      2. etcd
        Distributed key-value store
        Stores cluster state and configuration
        
        Examples stored:
        Pods
        Deployments
        Secrets
        ConfigMaps
        Node info
        
        Important
        If etcd is lost → cluster state lost

      3. kube-scheduler
        Decides which node a pod should run on
        
        Scheduling factors:
        CPU / Memory availability
        Node affinity
        Taints & tolerations
        Resource requests

      4. kube-controller-manager
        Runs controllers that maintain desired state.
        
        Examples:
        Node Controller
        Replication Controller
        Endpoint Controller
        Job Controller
        
        Example:
        Desired: 3 pods
        Running: 2 pods
        Controller → creates 1 more pod

  2️⃣ Worker Nodes (Where Applications Run)
    Definition
    Worker nodes are the machines that run the containerized workloads (pods).
  
      Each worker node contains:
      1. kubelet
        Agent running on each node.
        Responsibilities:
        Communicates with API Server
        Ensures containers inside pods are running
        Reports node status
        
        Example:
        API Server → Run pod nginx
        kubelet → pulls image and starts container
      
      2. Container Runtime
        Software responsible for running containers.
        
        Examples:
        containerd
        CRI-O
        Docker (older setups)
        
        Tasks:
        Pull images
        Run containers
        Manage container lifecycle
      
      3. kube-proxy
        Handles network communication inside cluster.
        
        Responsibilities:
        Maintains iptables / IPVS rules
        Enables Service networking
        Load balances traffic between pods
        
        Example:
        Service → nginx-service
        Traffic → kube-proxy → one of the pods

    3️⃣ How Everything Works Together
      Pod Creation Flow
      
      1️⃣ User runs
        kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
      2️⃣ Request goes to API Server
      3️⃣ API Server stores state in etcd
      4️⃣ Scheduler selects best node
      5️⃣ kubelet on that node receives instruction
      6️⃣ Container Runtime pulls image and runs container
      7️⃣ kube-proxy enables networking

🔴 Pods & Containers ----------------------------------
  1️⃣ Container
    Definition:
      A container is a lightweight, portable unit that packages an application with its dependencies and runtime.
    
    Key Concept:
      Runs using a container runtime (containerd, CRI-O)
      Created from container images (like Docker images)
      
    Important Points:
      Isolated process
      Has its own filesystem
      Starts quickly
      Ephemeral by nature
    
    Example"
      docker run nginx

    Interview Insight:
      Kubernetes does not manage containers directly. It manages them through Pods.

  2️⃣ Pod
    Definition:
      A Pod is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes that contains one or more containers.
      
    Key Concept:
      Containers inside a pod share resources.
    
    Shared resources:
      Network (same IP)
      Storage volumes
      Pod lifecycle

    Important Characteristics:
      One IP per Pod
      Usually One Container per Pod
      Pods are Ephemeral
      Pods are Managed by Controllers

🔴 Namespaces -----------------------------------
  1️⃣ Definition
    A Namespace is a logical partition inside a Kubernetes cluster used to organize and isolate resources.
    It allows multiple teams/applications to share the same cluster safely.
  
  2️⃣ Key Concept
    Namespaces provide resource separation within a cluster.
  
  Example:
    Cluster
       ├── Namespace: dev
       ├── Namespace: staging
       └── Namespace: production
    Each namespace can have its own pods, services, deployments, etc.
  
  3️⃣ Default Namespaces in Kubernetes
    Namespace	Purpose
    default	Used if no namespace specified
    kube-system	System components (DNS, scheduler, controller)
    kube-public	Publicly accessible resources
    kube-node-lease	Node heartbeat information

  4️⃣ Resource Isolation (Important)
    Namespaces help apply:
      Resource Quotas
      Network Policies
      RBAC access control
    
    Example:
      dev namespace
      CPU limit = 4 cores
      Memory = 8GB

  5️⃣ Important Commands
    kubectl get namespaces: get the existing namespaces
      Namespace	                       Purpose
      default	              Where resources go if no namespace is specified
      kube-system	          Kubernetes system components
      kube-public	          Publicly readable data
      kube-node-lease	      Node heartbeat information
    kubectl create namespace dev: create namespace for dev environment
    kubectl api-resources --namespaced=false: When you run you are listing Cluster-scoped resources only.
    kubectl api-resources --namespaced=false: When you run you are listing resources bound to namespace.
    kubectl get configmap -n <namespace>: To get the configmap created inside certain namespace.
    kubectl apply -f <configMapFile> --namespace=my-namespace: It will create configMap in my-namespace.
    Changing Active Namespace: Kubectx needs to be installed: <brew install kubectx>
    kubens: to get the list of availabe namespaces
    kubens <namespaceName>: To change The namespace
    kubectl get ns: lists all namespaces currently created in the cluster.

🔴 Labels & Selectors --------------------------------
  1️⃣ Labels
    Definition
    A Label is a key–value pair attached to Kubernetes objects (Pods, Services, Deployments, etc.) used for identification and grouping.
  
    Key Concept
      Labels help Kubernetes organize and select resources.
  
    Example:
      labels:
        app: nginx
        env: production
        tier: frontend

    Important Points about Labels:
      Attached to objects like:
        Pods
        Services
        Deployments
        Nodes

      Used for:
        Grouping
        Selection
        Filtering resources

      Example:
      kubectl get pods --show-labels

  2️⃣ Selectors
    Definition
      A Selector is used to identify and select objects based on labels.
      Controllers and Services use selectors to find the correct pods.
    
    Example:
      selector:
        app: nginx

    Where Selectors Are Used
      Selectors are used by:
        Services → find pods to send traffic
        ReplicaSets → manage pods
        Deployments → manage replicas
        NetworkPolicies
        kubectl filtering
        This selects all pods with label app=nginx.

  3️⃣ How Labels & Selectors Work Together
    Example:
    Pods:
      Pod1 → app=nginx
      Pod2 → app=nginx
      Pod3 → app=redis
    
    Service selector:
      selector:
        app: nginx
    
    Result:
      Service → Pod1
      Service → Pod2
      Pod3 is ignored.

🔴 kubectl Basics (Kubernetes CLI) ------------------------
  1️⃣ Definition
    kubectl is the command-line tool used to interact with a Kubernetes cluster.
    It communicates with the API Server to create, update, delete, and view cluster resources.

