    kubectl logs -l app=mongodb: selects the pod by its label and show the logs.
    kubectl get svc mongo-express-service: an inspection command used to view the networking details of a specific Service.
    kubectl port-forward svc/mongo-express-service 8081:8081\n: a networking tunnel that creates a direct link between your local machine (MacBook) and a Service inside your Kubernetes cluster.
                                                                Technically, it allows you to access a private cluster resource without setting up a complex LoadBalancer or Ingress.
    kubectl rollout restart deployment mongo-express: the "cleanest" way to reboot your application without changing your configuration or deleting the resource entirely.

🔴 Pod Lifecycle -------------------------------
  1️⃣ Definition
    Pod Lifecycle refers to the different phases a Pod goes through from creation to termination.
    It describes the state of a pod while Kubernetes manages it.

  2️⃣ Pod Lifecycle Flow
      Pod Created
           ↓
      Pending
           ↓
      Running
           ↓
      Succeeded / Failed
           ↓
      Terminated

  3️⃣ Pod Phases
    1️⃣ Pending
      Meaning
        Pod has been created but containers are not yet running.
      Reasons:
        Image pulling
        Node scheduling
        Resource allocation

    2️⃣ Running
      Meaning
      Pod is successfully scheduled and at least one container is running.

    3️⃣ Succeeded
      Meaning
      All containers in the pod completed successfully and exited.
      Common with:
        Jobs
        Batch workloads

    4️⃣ Failed
      Meaning
        At least one container terminated with an error.
      Possible reasons:
        Crash
        Application failure
        Resource issue

    5️⃣ Unknown
      Meaning
        Kubernetes cannot determine pod state.
      Reasons:
        Node communication failure
        Node crash
    
    4️⃣ Container States Inside Pod
      Each container inside a pod has its own state.
      
      🔘Waiting
        Container is waiting to start.
      
        Example reasons:
          ImagePullBackOff
          CrashLoopBackOff
        
      🔘Running
        Container is actively executing.
      
      🔘Terminated
        Container finished execution.
      
        Possible exit reasons:
          Completed
          Error
          OOMKilled

    5️⃣ Important Pod Conditions
      Conditions describe pod health.
      
      Examples:
        Condition	Meaning
        PodScheduled	         Pod assigned to node
        Initialized	           Init containers finished
        ContainersReady	       Containers ready
        Ready	                 Pod ready to serve traffic

    6️⃣ Pod Deletion Lifecycle
    
      When a pod is deleted:
        kubectl delete pod nginx
      
      Flow:
      Running
         ↓
      Terminating
         ↓
      Container stopped
         ↓
      Pod removed
      
      Grace period default:
      30 seconds
      
      Force delete:
      kubectl delete pod nginx --force --grace-period=0

    7️⃣ Restart Policies
    
      Pod restart behavior:
        Policy	                   Meaning
        Always	              Always restart container
        OnFailure	            Restart only if failure
        Never	                Do not restart

    8️⃣ Real Production Example

      Example issue:
        Pod → CrashLoopBackOff
      
      Meaning:
        Container keeps crashing
        Kubernetes keeps restarting it
      
      Debug steps:
        kubectl describe pod pod-name
        kubectl logs pod-name

🔴 Deployments ---------------------------------

  1️⃣ Definition
    A Deployment is a Kubernetes controller used to manage and maintain Pods and ReplicaSets for stateless applications.
    It ensures the desired number of pod replicas are always running.

  2️⃣ Key Concept
    Deployment manages pods indirectly.
      Deployment
           ↓
      ReplicaSet
           ↓
      Pods
    
    Deployment handles:
      Scaling
      Rolling updates
      Rollbacks
      Self-healing

  3️⃣ Why Deployments Are Used
  
    Without deployment:
      Pod crashes → Not automatically recreated
  
    With deployment:
      Pod crashes → ReplicaSet creates new pod
      Kubernetes ensures desired state = actual state.

  4️⃣ Example Deployment YAML
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: Deployment
    metadata:
      name: nginx-deployment
    spec:
      replicas: 3
      selector:
        matchLabels:
          app: nginx
      template:
        metadata:
          labels:
            app: nginx
        spec:
          containers:
          - name: nginx
            image: nginx
            ports:
            - containerPort: 80
  
    Create deployment:
      kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

  5️⃣ Key Features of Deployments
    Scaling - Increase or decrease pods.
    Rolling Updates - Update application without downtime.
    Rollback - Revert to previous version if update fails.
    Self Healing - Pod deleted/crashed
                      ↓
                  ReplicaSet creates new pod

  6️⃣ Real Production Example

    Example microservice deployment:
      payment-service
      replicas: 4
    
    Architecture:
      Deployment
         ↓
      ReplicaSet
         ↓
      Pod1
      Pod2
      Pod3
      Pod4

    If Pod2 crashes, Kubernetes creates Pod5 automatically.

🔴 ReplicaSet -----------------------------------

  1️⃣ Definition
    A ReplicaSet is a Kubernetes controller that ensures a specified number of identical Pods are always running in the cluster.
  
  2️⃣ Key Concept
    ReplicaSet maintains the desired number of pod replicas.

  3️⃣ How ReplicaSet Works
    ReplicaSet uses Labels & Selectors to identify which pods it manages.

    Example:
      selector:
        matchLabels:
          app: nginx

    ReplicaSet controls all pods with label app=nginx.

  4️⃣ ReplicaSet Example YAML
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: ReplicaSet
    metadata:
      name: nginx-rs
    spec:
      replicas: 3
      selector:
        matchLabels:
          app: nginx
      template:
        metadata:
          labels:
            app: nginx
        spec:
          containers:
          - name: nginx
            image: nginx

    Create ReplicaSet:
      kubectl apply -f replicaset.yaml

  5️⃣ Useful Commands
    kubectl get rs - 
    kubectl describe rs nginx-rs
    kubectl delete rs nginx-rs

🔴 DaemonSet ------------------------------

  1️⃣ Definition
    A DaemonSet is a Kubernetes controller that ensures a specific Pod runs on every node (or selected nodes) in the cluster.
  
  2️⃣ Key Concept
    Normal workloads:
      Deployment → runs some pods
      ReplicaSet → maintains pod count
  
    DaemonSet behavior:
      Each Node → 1 Pod
    
    Example:
      Node1 → Pod
      Node2 → Pod
      Node3 → Pod
  
    If a new node joins, DaemonSet automatically creates a pod on that node.

3️⃣ Why DaemonSets Are Used
  DaemonSets run node-level services that must exist on every node.

  Examples:
    Log collection
    Monitoring agents
    Networking plugins
    Security agents

  5️⃣ DaemonSet Example
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: DaemonSet
    metadata:
      name: fluentd-agent
    spec:
      selector:
        matchLabels:
          app: fluentd
      template:
        metadata:
          labels:
            app: fluentd
        spec:
          containers:
          - name: fluentd
            image: fluentd

    kubectl apply -f daemonset.yaml

  7️⃣ Useful Commands
  
    Get DaemonSets:
      kubectl get daemonsets
    
    Get pods:
      kubectl get pods
    
    Describe DaemonSet:
      kubectl describe daemonset fluentd-agent


