🔴 Ingress ====================================================================================
  🚩“Ingress does not replace Kubernetes Services. It operates at the HTTP layer and routes external traffic to Services, 
    which in turn load-balance traffic to Pods. Ingress often replaces the need for multiple NodePort or LoadBalancer services, 
    but Services are still mandatory.”

  🚩 An Ingress Controller is a Kubernetes component that actually implements Ingress rules by running 
     a reverse proxy / load balancer (like NGINX, HAProxy, Envoy).
      Ingress = rules
      Ingress Controller = engine that enforces those rules
      🔧 What the Ingress Controller Actually Does --
          Terminates TLS (HTTPS)
          Path-based routing (/api, /app)
          Host-based routing (app.example.com)
          Load balancing
          Health checks
          Rewrites, redirects, rate limits (controller-specific)

    minikube addons enable ingress: to enable ingress controller in cluster.
    kubectl get deployment -A | grep ingress: give all the pods filter by ingress
    minikube addons list: get the list of all addons
    minikube addons enable <addon> : To enable the addons
    kubectl get ingress -n kubernetes-dashboard: 
    kubectl get ingress -n kubernetes-dashboard --watch: get into live mode
    kubectl describe ingress dashboard-ingress -n kubernetes-dashboard: you are asking Kubernetes for a detailed 
                                                                        "status report" of your Ingress resource

    sudo vim /etc/hosts: opening your Mac's Local DNS Resolver file with administrative privileges.
      "By editing this file, you tell your Mac: "Before you go to the internet, check this list first. 
      If you see 'dashboard.com', send the traffic to my Minikube IP instead."

    🧲 Real-time Scenario ------ 
        1️⃣ Issue
        Kubernetes Dashboard not accessible via Ingress and custom domain on Minikube.
        
        2️⃣ Symptoms
        dashboard.com opens blank page or fails to load
        Dashboard not visible despite Ingress controller and DNS mapping
        Service remains inaccessible externally
        
        3️⃣ Root Cause
        Kubernetes Dashboard is not exposed via Ingress by default. On Minikube, Ingress has no real external IP and the dashboard requires authenticated, secure access.
        
        4️⃣ Troubleshooting
        Verified Ingress controller was running
        Confirmed DNS resolution was correct
        Checked dashboard service type (ClusterIP)
        Identified absence of Ingress resource for dashboard
        Observed authentication requirement for dashboard access
        
        5️⃣ Resolution
        Used minikube dashboard, which:
        Starts a local secure proxy on the host machine
        Forwards traffic directly to the dashboard’s ClusterIP service
        Uses current kubeconfig for authentication
        Manages TLS internally
        Opens the dashboard in the browser without external exposure  



  🧲 Real-time Scenario ------ 
      1. Issue
        Ingress controller pod not visible in kube-system namespace after installation.

      2. Symptoms
        kubectl get pods -n kube-system did not show ingress controller pod
        kubectl get pods -A | grep ingress showed ingress controller running

      3. Root Cause
        Ingress controller is not a core Kubernetes component and was installed by Minikube in the ingress-nginx namespace, not kube-system.

      4. Troubleshooting Steps
        Listed pods across all namespaces using <kubectl get pods -A>
        Identified ingress controller running in ingress-nginx namespace
        Verified by running <kubectl get pods -n ingress-nginx>

      5. Resolution
        Confirmed ingress controller was correctly deployed in ingress-nginx; no action required.

🔴 Real-time Scenario =========================================================================
  🐞 Issue ----------------------------
    mongo-express UI returns “Unauthorized” after exposing service via Minikube.
  
  📌 Symptoms --
    mongo-express pod was in Running state
    Service was created as NodePort
    Running:
      <minikube service mongo-express-service>
    opened:
      <http://127.0.0.1:<random-port>>
    Browser consistently returned:
      "Unauthorized"
  
  🔍 Root Cause ----------------------
    When using Minikube with Docker/OrbStack driver on macOS, NodePort services are exposed via a local tunnel, which maps the service to a random localhost port.
    The redirection from NodePort → 127.0.0.1:<random-port> was expected behavior, not an error.
    The actual issue was application-level:
    mongo-express enables Basic Authentication by default
    Only MongoDB connection credentials were configured using:
      ME_CONFIG_MONGODB_ADMINUSERNAME
      ME_CONFIG_MONGODB_ADMINPASSWORD
    No UI authentication credentials were configured
    Basic Auth was not explicitly disabled
    As a result, mongo-express rejected all requests with 401 Unauthorized
  
  🛠️ Troubleshooting Steps Taken ----------------------------
    1️⃣ Verified Pod and Service Health
      kubectl get pods
      kubectl get svc mongo-express-service
      Pod was running
      Service existed and correctly mapped
    
    2️⃣ Identified macOS + Minikube NodePort Behavior
      Observed that Minikube exposed the service on:
      http://127.0.0.1:<random-port>
      Confirmed this was expected due to Docker/OrbStack driver
    
    3️⃣ Eliminated Networking as Root Cause
      Used port forwarding to bypass Service and NodePort:
      kubectl port-forward svc/mongo-express-service 8081:8081
      Issue still persisted → confirmed not a Kubernetes networking problem
    
    4️⃣ Inspected Application Configuration
      kubectl describe pod <mongo-express-pod-name>
      Verified environment variables
      Found only MongoDB credentials configured
      No ME_CONFIG_BASICAUTH settings present
    
    5️⃣ Applied Fix (Disable UI Authentication)
      Edited deployment:
      kubectl edit deployment mongo-express
      Added:
        - name: ME_CONFIG_BASICAUTH
          value: "false"
    
    6️⃣ Restarted Application Pods
      kubectl rollout restart deployment mongo-express
    
    7️⃣ Re-tested Access
      kubectl port-forward svc/mongo-express-service 8081:8081
      Accessed:
        http://localhost:8081
        mongo-express UI loaded successfully without Unauthorized
  
    ✅ Final Resolution ----------------------
      The issue was caused by default Basic Authentication enabled in mongo-express
      Explicitly disabling Basic Auth and restarting the pod resolved the issue
      Kubernetes networking and service exposure were functioning correctly


🔴 Helm ====================================================
  Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes.
  Helm helps you define, install, upgrade, and manage Kubernetes applications using reusable templates called Charts.

  🚩 Core Helm Concepts ------
    1️⃣ Chart
      A Helm Chart is a packaged Kubernetes application.
      A chart contains:
        mychart/
          Chart.yaml        # Metadata
          values.yaml       # Default values
          templates/        # Kubernetes YAML templates
          charts/           # Dependencies
            
    2️⃣ Release
      When you install a chart in a cluster:
        <<< helm install my-app ./mychart >>>

      You create a Release.
        A release = running instance of a chart
        One chart → multiple releases possible
        Each release has revision history

    3️⃣ Values.yaml
      This file contains configurable parameters.
      Example:
        replicaCount: 2
        image:
          repository: nginx
          tag: latest
        
      You override values:
        <<< helm install my-app ./mychart -f prod-values.yaml >>>

    4️⃣ Templates
      Helm uses Go templating engine.
      Example inside deployment.yaml:
        <<< replicas: {{ .Values.replicaCount }} >>>

      Helm dynamically replaces values during install.

    5️⃣ Repository
      A place where charts are stored.
      Example:
        helm repo add bitnami https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami
    
      Popular repositories:
        Bitnami
        ArtifactHub

  🚩 Helm Workflow (Step-by-Step) --------
    1. Add repository
    <<< helm repo add bitnami https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami >>>
    
    2. Search chart
    <<< helm search repo nginx >>>
    
    3. Install chart
    <<< helm install my-nginx bitnami/nginx >>>
    
    4. List releases
    <<< helm list >>>
    
    5. Upgrade
    <<< helm upgrade my-nginx bitnami/nginx >>>
    
    6. Rollback
    <<< helm rollback my-nginx 1 >>>
    
    7. Uninstall
    <<< helm uninstall my-nginx >>>


  🚩 Helm v2 vs Helm v3
      Feature	                  Helm v2	              Helm v3
      Tiller (server component)	Required	            ❌ Removed
      Security	                RBAC issues	          More secure
      Release storage	          ConfigMaps	          Secrets
      Architecture	            Client-Server	        Client-only

  🚀 Helm in Real DevOps / SRE World
    Since you're preparing for DevOps/SRE roles, this is how Helm is used in production:

    🔹 With CI/CD
      Build image
      Update image tag in values.yaml
      helm upgrade --install
      Automated rollout
    
    🔹 With GitOps (ArgoCD / Flux)
      Charts stored in Git
      ArgoCD syncs automatically
    
    🔹 Blue-Green / Canary
      Use different releases
      Adjust replica weights

🔴 Storage Class ==================================================
  a StorageClass defines how storage should be dynamically provisioned.
  🎯 Why StorageClass Is Needed
    Without StorageClass:
      Admin must manually create PVs
      Developers depend on infra team
      Scaling becomes difficult
    
    With StorageClass:
      PVC triggers automatic volume creation
      No manual PV creation needed
      Works seamlessly in cloud environments

  🏗️ Storage Architecture Flow
    Pod → PVC → StorageClass → Provisioner → PV → Cloud Disk

  Flow Explained:
    Developer creates PVC
    PVC references a StorageClass
    Kubernetes calls provisioner
    PV is dynamically created
    Pod mounts the PVC

  🆚 StorageClass vs PersistentVolume
  Feature	 -               StorageClass	                        PersistentVolume
  Purpose	 -               Defines how storage is created	      Represents actual storage
  Dynamic provisioning -	 Yes	                                No
  Cloud integration	  -    Yes	                                Manual


🔴 Stateful vs Stateless Applications in Kubernetes =======================================

  1️⃣ Stateless Applications --------
  📌 Definition
    A stateless application does NOT store client/session data locally.
    Each request is independent.
    
    If the pod dies → nothing is lost.

  🧠 Characteristics
    No local storage dependency
    Easily scalable (horizontal scaling)
    Any replica can handle any request
    No fixed identity
    No need for Persistent Volumes

  💡 Examples
    Nginx (web server)
    Apache HTTP Server
    Frontend React apps
    API gateways
    Microservices

  📦 Kubernetes Deployment Used
    Stateless apps typically use:
    kind: Deployment

  2️⃣ Stateful Applications --------
  📌 Definition
    A stateful application stores data locally or maintains session/state information.

    If the pod dies → data must NOT be lost.

  🧠 Characteristics
    Requires persistent storage
    Each pod has unique identity
    Ordered startup & shutdown
    Stable network identity
    Uses Persistent Volume

  💡 Examples
    MySQL
    PostgreSQL
    MongoDB
    Redis
    Kafka
    Elasticsearch

  📦 Kubernetes Resource Used
    Stateful apps use:
    kind: StatefulSet









        
